<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Jones, John. Letter to Judge Adam Mabane, 1787, with a copy of Jones's testimony 1783. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0003</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p class="head"><span class="AddHand-editors">[Letter to John Jones from Adam Mabane Esq., 1787]</span></p>
<p><span class="fw">1</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">To The Honorable Adam Mabane Esq<sub>r</sub></p>
<p style="text-align:right;"><span class="DelHand-author">Chief</span><span class="AddHand-author"> Senior</span> Judge of the Court of</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">Common Pleas: for the District</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">of Quebec.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Sir</p>
<p class="positiveIndent">The Public will be surprised to see me enter into Correspondence with you; it is with reluctance I undertake the task, tho' in defence of my Character; the Public shall decide on the propriety of this Letter: I hope to convince them that the Comments you have made on the testimony, which I gave in the Court of Enquiry, contain assertions unsupported by facts, and are the effusions of an illiberal embittered Mind.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Truth is Truth wherever to be found: the honor of Government is equally concerned, and the ends  of Public Justice will be equally answered, by the attainments of Truth from a private individual as from a Magistrate of high authority; in Search of it was I called upon <span class="AddHand-author">to give testimony, </span><span class="AddHand-editors">[and]</span> the Letter &amp; Spirit of your Comments <span class="DelHand-author">on my testimony</span> amount to this; that I am a perjured</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">JJ</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">Man</p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[1]</span></p>

</div>
